<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06112138 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06112138 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  Seeking to further ease economic sanctions, South African President F.W. deKlerk was in Britain on Saturday awaiting talks with leaders on the progressof reforms to end apartheid. De Klerk's official visit starts Monday when hemeets British Prime Minister John Major for the first time. In recognition ofde Klerk's efforts to end South Africa's policies of racial segregation,European Economic Community nations last week lifted most of the remainingsanctions, including bans on imports of South African iron, steel and goldcoins. Bans remain on arms trade, military cooperation and sports.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  DE KLERK TO BRIEF MAJOR ON REFORMS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Foreign News in Brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910421  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  18A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  98  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday April 21, 199100112138,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>